text:
i didnâ€™t expect to be here right now. honesty, i thought i would be dead.

either from suicide or from obesity. i just didnâ€™t expect â€œthrivingâ€ to be a possibility when i spent my whole life just trying to survive.

i was heavily bullied in school. rumours, fat jokes, pranks, you name it.

my past of being sexually molested at the age of 3 haunted me. i was raped at 14 by a classmate. the loss of my first child due to my health left me feeling like a failure.

i remember in one of my darkest moments, when the pain was too much, the depression was deep, i planned my suicide.

i put on a happy face and pretended to be happy but the reality is, i was dying inside.

i felt so out of control that i thought my only way to escape out of how i was feeling was just to end it.

at over 300lb, i couldnâ€™t stop binging on food. food for me was my alcohol and i needed it to keep me sane. it was my escape from reality and it was going to kill me one way or another.

i saw no way out. i was ready to leave this world.

but i couldnâ€™t. see, there was this one thing that kept me here.

a tiny human, who shared my body with me for 9 months. a beautiful little boy who gave me unconditional love.

i struggled with post partum depression, and what most moms donâ€™t admit to, is having thoughts of suicide. all my past trauma magnified by 1000 with ppd.

i battled with it for 3 years after my son was born, and i felt again like a failure. i just didnâ€™t feel like i could be the mother he needed. i was damaged.

but... one beautiful spring day, i was sent a very loud message from the universe that it was time to take care of myself and learn to love myself just as much as he loved me.

that day, he ran from me at the park while we were playing, and my heavy frame was unable to catch up with him. he bolted out the gates and into the street. a black mazda halted inches from his tiny blonde head.

in that moment, i woke up. i had so much love around me and because i only focused on the pain, i almost missed out on the best part of my life.

to this day, he is my driving force to love my life as happy and healthy as i can be. i want to show him just how much of a survivor his mama is. â¤

text:
when you raise your voice be prepared to be victim blamed and laughed upon.
be prepared to loose all those people whom you thought are your frnds, be prepared to be left alone in the darkness,be prepared to be laughed at and talk about and be prepared to be a survivor. if you can conquer this then you can conquer anything in life.
to all the survivor and victims,never let anyone to dim your lite or allow yourself to question your character..the one who speaks bad about you is the reflection of who they are and not who you are. similar way the one who caused this to you is the reflection of who they are and not who you are. do not expect justice from humans for they are not superior to god. when god gives justice then he will give it through numerous ways and one of the way is that you survived. #metoo #nomore

text:
i open my heart 
not with carelessness,
but with humility. 
so you can read 
the foreign language 
that is trapped inside my chest.
that i cannot comprehend myself,
so that you can tell me 
what i truly feel,
because this foreign language 
is becoming too difficult 
to carry
myself.
-

text:
happy late birthday sir elton joel. 
so much hair, so much more love. he never leaves my side and never let's me down. he begs too much and never stays off my lap but hey, i'll take it. having an #emotionalsupportanimal through college has been the most beneficial thing to come. he is my rock, my blanket, who i tell all my secrets to. my little man who isn't so little anymore. late nights of studying and pulling overnights, the constant panic attacks, breakups, sick times, and just all over bad days are made possible by yours truelly, sir elton joel.

text:
for all the times iâ€™ve said no, that have been brushed away, ignored.. not taken seriously.. anger bubbles.. why wasnâ€™t i heard? â€¢
an underlying confusion: should i have been louder, clearer, more determined?
â€¢
it takes two for sure, and at some point it just seems easier to give in than be demanding.. i mean.. how many times do i have to say it? do you not think i know what i want and donâ€™t?!
â€¢
amidst that there is shame, doubt, and a questioning.. does it really mean anything? does it matter? is it all silliness..
â€¢
if i were speaking to another it would be very clear.. â€¢
no means no..
â€¢
yet, being personally involved, doubt bubbles.. it can seem so small, so insignificant.. and at the same time it hurts so deep.. some sort of betrayal to the self..
â€¢

text:
my final piece for the 'vessel' ceramics project on my art and design course. i had loads of fun making this, and researching it and all the different ideas behind it.
the mug has "smash the patriarchy" stamped on it, there are pieces referring to various movements that i have been inspired by and that j think have done a lot for women. i also added in a cotton placenta with a white tampon style string on the inside of the cup. i find it ironic that the placenta is what feeds and keeps us all thriving before we are born yet men are disgusted by it and all the "stuff" that makes us females. they don't understand that they're not here without us! 
#smashthepatriarchy #feminist #stronggirlsclub #repeal #metoo #timesup #nastywoman 
#artanddesign #carlislecollege

have you tried the exercise thing, but fell off one too many times?
or

who you are, and how to approach health (yes food & fitness) gods way! 
it's time to cut the yo yo sting, the comparison string, the not good enough string, the doubting string, the excuses string.

lets learn how to truly honor our bodies, the way god calls us to, and fall in love with doing it!

text:
victimisation- level 1 of the pyramid refers to things that people generally find acceptable, harmless, easier to ignore or fail to see how it plays into rape culture. rape culture starts with normalisation.
degradation- level 2  of the pyramid refers to issues that threaten the dignity of victims and causes violation and lack of respect.
removal of autonomy- level 3 of the pyramid refers to acts that take place when a victim is no longer in control, these acts infringe on their freedom. 
explicit violence- level 4 of the pyramid are acts of violence.

morgenavond  is het zover! nog even ook wat praktische informatie voor de avond. inloop en last minute kaartverkoop start om 18.20 tot 18.50. wij hebben een strak programma en het wordt erg gewaardeerd om ruim op tijd aanwezig te zijn. om 19.00 stipt begint het programma. vanaf 19.15 gaan de deuren dicht.

het adres is: anna van buerenplein 301, 2595 dg, den haag

met ov: op 1 minuut loopafstand van den haag centraal.
loop naar het luc-gebouw (leiden university college), waar voor het gebouw iemand van de organisatie staat om de weg te wijzen.

programma in het kort:
opening
1e spreker: dr. karim
2e spreker: dr. van middelburg
interview met ervaringsdeskundige: mw. fatima
v&a
afsluiting
borrel bij de minglemush ------------------------------------------- the event is happening tomorrow evening! below you can find some practical information regarding the schedule, as well as the location.

registration and last-minute ticket sales start at 18:20 until 18:50. make sure you are on time, as this will ensure a smooth start of the event. the event starts at 19:00, and the doors close at 19:15.

the address is anna van buerenplein 301, 2595dg, the hague.

you can get there via public transport. once you get to the hague central station, walk out to the leiden university college building, where someone from montium will be waiting to show the way.

program in short:
opening
1st speaker: dr. karim
2nd speaker: dr. van middelburg
interview with an fgm-survivor: fatima
q&a
end of event
drinks at minglemush

text:
i never planned on posting this for all the reasons youâ€™d think: i hate my body, i have stretch marks, i have cellulite everywhere, i will never have a thigh gap, etc. 
my wonderful and talented friend, @missfitphoto, took these for my 40th birthday last year... these were for me. this was also cathartic. i cried, but felt a wave of release come over me. 
written all over my body are just a fraction of the things he said to me. though i shared my story of abuse publicly, one of you shared my story with him. 
this is my reality. i might be â€œcrazyâ€ or â€œimpulsiveâ€ or â€œfatâ€ or â€œuglyâ€ or â€œnever look good in a bathing suitâ€, but iâ€™m the one who is still healing. i have scars all over my heart and soul. yâ€™all can say whatever you want... but it doesnâ€™t take away from the fact that i went through what i went through. this is my life and my story. i wonâ€™t be apologizing anymore. i wonâ€™t live to impress anyone anymore. if you donâ€™t believe me, i donâ€™t care. this is my reality and i believe women. #unafraid

they are, more and more, understood to be the victims of â€œrape cultureâ€ â€” the disgusting but pervasive notion that sexual violence is something to be normalized and trivialized.

text:

text:
ajay sathyan is a survivor of child abuse, rape, suicide attempt and police brutality, who fled india to protect his dignity and life. ajay's life has been a constant battle to survive violence and brutality instigated by patriarchal standards. now, in europe ajay's faced with toxic whiteness along with regressive patriarchal systems. through his many attempts to secour help (fearing suicide), ajay was forced to live with disappointment and blame. now, ajay has taken the mantle to express his pain, angst, fear, disappointment, depression, wit, critique and maybe humor through art. also, ajay is on the verge of completing an autobiography and hopefully, publish few works of fiction later.

text:
***trigger warning: sexual assault/rape

hereâ€™s the logo design created by my significant other @deleonjullian for dead girl rising, or in its abbreviated form dgr. thanks baby! love you! â¤ï¸itâ€™s placed over some headlines that have served as inspiration when writing my music. iâ€™m a survivor of childhood sexual abuse. when i see these types of headlines, it makes me upset, sad, angry. it reminds me of some of my negative experiences. this is why i put a trigger warning at the top, because i know how triggering these headlines can be in stirring up memories, and emotions. while researching articles for this, my bf and i got so sad reading about it. if youâ€™re someone whose also experienced sexual abuse traumas, know that you are not alone, there are so many people going through the same things. the sadness, the guilt, the thoughts of suicide, feeling dirty. healing is possible! hold on, youâ€™ll build resilience, youâ€™ll keep going! you will do great things! if you are down today, you can rise again tomorrow! #metoo #endsexualviolence #endsexualabuse #believeher #rise #torontomusician #pianorock #feminist #womensrights #womensrightsarehumanrights #endviolenceagainstwomen #endviolenceagainstsexworkers #endviolenceagainstwomenandgirls #feminism #riotgrrrl #riotgrrrls #experimentalrock #gothicpiano

text:
before that nerve-wrecking moment the only form in which blood existed for her 6 year old self was in her veins and it could only ooze out when she would get a paper-cut or would injure her finger with scissors. she would cry in panic each time she'd injure herself for the sight of blood horrified her. 
it was on a life-changing winter evening when she discovered a new outlet of blood flow in her body. although the outlet was new, she could still identify with the excruciating pain that paved way for blood flow from her 'forbidden part', the only senstation that became a bridge for her to remain consciously in touch with her former self. however, this time she didn't cry or crib. perhaps her pain had overpowered her emotions? this time a familiar hand had covered her face, a hand that would reward her with candies if she maintained silence. the coarse voice belonging to the familiar hand reassured her that she would get candies. it reiterated the fact that she's a good girl and that it should remain a secret. 
his secret still remains. in the form of a burden that she's bearing on her body, mind and soul. the familiar hand stained with her virgin blood suffocates her as it still covers her mouth. however, over these 16 years the familiar hand has taken the place of her conscious drenched in sorrow and smothered in the memory of the most excruciating abdominal pain she had ever endured in all these years. the hand is that of a conscious that trembles at the thought of surfacing her grief and leads her to collapsing, time and again. however, the secret remains. virgin blood of her 6 year old self smothered on her face, protects the secret of that beast and will continue doing so for all times to come. -to those silent sufferers.

it was on a life-changing winter evening when she discovered a new outlet of blood flow in her body. although the outlet was new, she could still identify with the excruciating pain that paved way for blood flow from her 'forbidden part', the only senstation that became a bridge for her to remain consciously in touch with her former self. however, this time she didn't cry or crib. perhaps her pain had overpowered her emotions? this time a familiar hand had covered her face, a hand that would reward her with candies if she maintained silence. the coarse voice belonging to the familiar hand reassured her that she would get candies. it reiterated the fact that she's a good girl and that it should remain a secret. 
his secret still remains. in the form of a burden that she's bearing on her body, mind and soul. the familiar hand stained with her virgin blood suffocates her as it still covers her mouth. however, over these 16 years the familiar hand has taken the place of her conscious drenched in sorrow and smothered in the memory of the most excruciating abdominal pain she had ever endured in all these years. the hand is that of a conscious that trembles at the thought of surfacing her grief and leads her to collapsing, time and again. however, the secret remains. virgin blood of her 6 year old self smothered on her face, protects the secret of that beast and will continue doing so for all times to come. -to those silent sufferers.

text:
do not touch her:
a free-spirited girl, very liberal, consumed in her bravado. 
you thought you could touch her, and she'd be okay with it. 
she is so comfortable in her body, she is pleased with it. she wouldn't mind if you get comfortable with it too, right?

she shows it off, like an armour, an armour can be played with, armour is not skin, it can belong to anyone. even you, right? 
wrong! don't touch it, you will burn her. she is not to be held.
 she is not to be misunderstood. 
her freedom is not an open invitation or call of desperation. it is her right! 
just let her be. don't touch her.
.
.
.
.

text:
this is something i never talk about publicly, and likely never will again. but while i want to keep some parts of my life private, i decided i should share something, to remove any stigma or shame of this diagnosis and to remind myself that i am a patient too. this month, i am celebrating a particular anniversary of being cancer free myself. 
years ago, i was diagnosed with a very early stage of a very lethal cancer. thankfully it was found early and only required surgery to remove it. i was extremely fortunate not to need any chemotherapy or radiation, or any other treatments. while mind-numbing at the time, i talked to my siblings and parents, to make sure they were evaluated as well, and went forward with the procedure. yet my scar reminds me that i am mortal, and that maybe worrying over something silly just isn't worth the breath in my lungs.

there is always a small voice in the back of my mind that reminds me it could return any day. i get screened for recurrence, and am vigilant for signs and symptoms. if it truly returned, i would not last a year. but i choose not to think like that, i simply can't. instead of focusing on my mortality, i choose to make every attempt to live in the moment and focus on what it means to live - and yes, that means giving in to some disagreements or particular demands from my kids. (i mean, who cares if they have another spoonful of nutella?? there must be some protein in there....) as my husband says, this won't be the hill i die on. and he's right. my hill is a long way away.
name: Niamey Wilson, MD, FACS

text:
the 3 essential p of life: passion, persistence, perseverance. .
.
.
this picture was taken on november 08th, 2016, in nanjing, china. my poster was presented as indonesia's only representative on 2016 international pharmacy forum by fip x china pharmaceutical university.
.
.
.
i'll tell you the truth; it's always bizzare even to me, about my whole journey as a pharmacy student. how did i finished my journey is as much mysterious as how i was there at the first place.
.
.
often people come to me; "but you did achieve here and there, this and that"
.
.
maybe, it was because i always believe that i have to excell my capacities, to finish what has been started (this is also often the reason why i received many snickers, or being worried too much. maybe) .
.
.
so here i am today, in early 2019, staring at the old pictures of achieving the impossible. i'm sitting here, while holding to pixar studio and oscar statues photos, things that mattered. have i poured the 3 essential p these far, toward it? i guess i haven't. am i afraid? yes. am i competitive? honestly, yes. .
.
but will i give up? no. because comparing can never bring me anywhere. so, even if i'm afraid, bring it on! i'm ready, and i will always be prepared. .
.
#byl #thechroniclesofl #ltravellouge #china #nanjing #passion #persistence #perseverance #love #instagood #instapic #leanit #pictures #happiness #travelling #metoo

text: whether you realize it or not, recovery from addiction is a revolutionary act in the truest sense. it is a radical re-ordering of self. first is the emotionally violent overthrow of the old way, followed by a period of excitement and newness. lastly comes the difficult work of normalizing the new way. keep in mind that your new boundaries, views, attitudes, and beliefs can cause conflict with those who may welcome your sobriety, but be threatened by your recovery. we occupy a fixed position the minds of some and the further we go in recovery the more we challenge a dynamic that has suited them more than it has suited us. remain alert, tread lightly and arm yourself with kindness, but always be prepared for the ambush, to defend yourself against those who repeatedly say they are proud of you, yet always seem to find a reason to deny, belittle or otherwise punish you. most people are kind and do genuinely care, but kindness is also a veil behind which those who wish to harm you will hide in plain sight. there are those who will prey on people in early recovery. as radical feminism and whisper networks become more entrenched, men especially must be vigilant when welcoming unfamiliar females into their lives because far more than your recovery is at stake. #recoverywarrior #recoveryrevolution #soberlifestyle #metoo #radicalfeminism #staystrong #knowledgeisgrowth #calumnias #existentialism #readbooks #autodidactism #selfcare #besafe #rudeboys

.
.

.
.

#
signs at a â€œ#metooâ€ demonstration during the second annual womenâ€™s march in cambridge, mass., january 20, 2018. (brian snyder/reuters) i was traveling friday and missed a rather interesting and consequential story. lisa borders, the ceo of timeâ€™s up, an â€œorganization born of the #metoo movement that advocates for safe and harassment-free workplaces,â€ has resigned. why? because her son was accused of sexual assault. but thatâ€™s not what makes the story truly notable. family troubles can cause people to press pause on their careers all the time. whatâ€™s notable is that the ceo resigned in part to advocate for her sonâ€™s innocence: borders made it clear to timeâ€™s up leadership that she planned to proactively defend her son, someone close to the situation who was not authorized to discuss it publicly, and so spoke on the condition of anonymity, told the washington post. this created a difficult tension within the organization, whose mission revolves around believing survivors of sexual abuse. in response, timeâ€™s up put out a statement that said, in part, that it â€œunequivocally supports all survivors of sexual harassment and abuseâ€ and that â€œall of our actions were fully guided by our support for survivors.â€ hereâ€™s the statement inâ€¦

pastor ken simmons

text: our bodies, including our brains, naturally react to events in certain ways. neurofeedback has the ability to increase stability and resiliency in the face of traumatic stress in ways that have not been permanently possible with drugs or talk therapy alone. many of these reactions have not been within our cognitive awareness or control. neurofeedback empowers the brain to more quickly and easily make changes in neuropathways that lead to flourishing, and this is why i cannot help but study in this field. i am excited to share that my professional journey into biofeedback and neurofeedback has officially begun and i am looking forward to seeing how it helps clients in my coaching practice. #lovepoweredlife #neurofeedback #heartmath #1john418

text:
in talk at notre dame, #metoo founder says the movement's goal is 'the work of healing'
by south bend tribune reporter greg swiercz
south bend â€” tarana burke launched the metoo movement in 2006 but it changed dramatically in 2017, when the hashtag #metoo unleashed a worldwide social media phenomenon that focused on sexual assault.
burke explained the evolution of the movement â€” from her journey of discovery as a teen to the impact that #metoo has had in confronting sexual violence â€” at the university of notre dame on monday night, in a conversation with notre dame professor maria mckenna in the debartolo classroom building.
burke is senior director at girls for gender equity in brooklyn. there, as in her early life, she helps girls coping with the effects of sexual violence.

text:
as a little girl i was told to walk quietly so i walked on my toes, to speak when spoken to so i held my tongue. donâ€™t draw attention to yourself with outfits, donâ€™t eat too much because fat is unattractive,  donâ€™t talk back in case it makes people angry, donâ€™t cry in public, be humble, donâ€™t make a scene, avoid conflict and lastly to be myself. ha! 
basically i was trained to be invisible. i have always been a good fly on the wall. on stage and in my writing is where i now have a voice, a face and an outfit that stands out. 
i am not blaming, we are all doing our best but i am aware of how this impacted me and i recognize similar behaviours in some of my vocal students today. 
social obedience and control led me to depression, repression, alcohol abuse, years of therapy and into and out of abusive relationships where i tolerated too much bad behaviour because i didnâ€™t know myself enough to stand up for myself or have a voice. 
change comes through educating young girls of their human rights to respect, freedom of speech, choice and safety. these concepts have to be taught and encouraged if we want transformation.
 letâ€™s let our daughters, youth and students know they are worthy and  loved no matter what. donâ€™t always expect more from them. if they are loved and heard and seen they will gain the confidence to become all they can be. 
we are all unique, here on purpose and for a reason and canâ€™t spread our wings unless we are grounded and know we are special already.  we are good enough as we are. we donâ€™t have to prove it or conform to be loved. then we can make our make a sound, own ourselves, speak our truth, be a vision even if it may create discomfort and conflict for those around us. .

text:
grateful to have caroline macgillivray part of our panel for this year's women's awareness week  #iwd2019 in vancouver. .
.
caroline macgillivray designs workshops and programs to promote health and wellness in the corporate and not for profit sector. caroline is a popular speaker, writer, medical qi gong therapist, yoga teacher and workshop leader.  she believes we need to unplug, breathe and be. she is has been involved with  initiatives such as qi day and bunny yoga fundraising classes for small animal rescue. she has also taught workshops for kids and parents for safe online outreach society.  caroline is best known for founding beauty night society, an award-winning charity that provides programs to build self esteem and change the lives of vulnerable people through wellness, life skills development and make overs. in 18 years, beauty night society has given 70, 000 life-makeovers to women who live in poverty.
.
. 
the well beings & weekend rituals (march 4, 9 & 10) https://iwd2019vancouver.eventbrite.ca or the link in @minibarcanadaâ€™s profile.

text:
as far as i have come with my ppd i still have really hard days.  they are few and far between but they can hit like a ton of bricks.  the hardest thing to do on those days is to allow myself to withdraw from family activities and to take alone time.  itâ€™s not that i donâ€™t want it, but there is a guilt i associate with it.  will i miss out on the kids doing something for the first time? will my husband be resentful if he has them by himself all day? am i being dramatic? is this selfish? 
the answer is no.  and while itâ€™s easier said then done it is necessary.  we must take care of ourselves.  we must listen to our bodies and our minds.  it doesnâ€™t have to be all day but it should be for a bit every day. take a walk, take a run, listen to some music, take a long shower, do something for you. ğŸ˜˜

text:
preach. louder. bolder. 
the age is now and here, we are going to make this world better with or without mass support. 
however, it does seem like our society is not all that bad and that it does correct its past mistakes.
it does use common sense, it learns to become better, just a little sensitising is needed. 
that's why, here is my voice, preaching loudly, boldly.

text:
guess what y'all? we are a few days away from #womenshistory month and we are so excited to get started with posts about women. for too long, women and our ideas were kept in the background. can you believe that in 2019 there are still spaces that silence women? i have attended several churches where there are no women in leadership, yet the majority of the congregation is made up of women. how do we continue to allow this? women have amazing, important, and relevant ideas and perspectives that are beneficial to all. stand up and be heard! push past the fear of anonymity and be counted for your great ideas.  i want to congratulate all of you beautiful and wonderfully made women.  you are seen and appreciated! give yourself a big loving hug! you're so important!â €
.â €
.â €
.â €

text:
(1/2) you sit across me, deep in thought, you stroke your lips as you stare into nothingness. there's a heaviness in your presence, like you carry the weight of the entire world on your chest. there is a sadness about your eyes, like they could cry a million tears and never dry. those creases at the corners are the intricacies of an artist. that makes me believe in god. your eyes bring out the mother in me, i want to cradle you in my arms and put your sorrows to sleep. poetry flows from the folds of your forehead as you frown. you hum an almost recognisable tune, the song of loss. the reddish corners of your eye, burn with passion yet speak of longing in cold nights. your artistic fingertips is where i want to find myself. you catch me looking at you and there's sultry in my glances, you raise your eyebrow questioning me, my heart beats a little bit faster, a rhythm so divine. i look out the door as usual, and wonder why i always have my eyes on the exit. you walk towards my chair, there is a sense of belonging to the way i inhale the smell of your cologne mixed with your own scent, but it's followed by an exhale of what screams of abandonment, like someone inside me wailing for someone that never left. my body tells me this won't last. i ignore every ounce of it. we engage in a conversation. somewhere your words never find me, and mine never find yours. a mundane conversation. i nod. you nod. i look into your eyes, your's fixated on mine. you slide you fingers through my hair playfully, it mutes the entire room crowded with noisy strangers. some mundane conversation? again. somewhere you put in a sentence so heavy that my heart can't take it. what have you been through? i wonder. what about you feels so close yet distant? what is it? i can't put my finger on it. i move across the tables and reach for the exit. it's time to leave. like you will, someday? maybe. you reach for a hug, curl your arms around me. i reciprocate. marlboro, hmm. your breath is warm. it touches my face the way sunlight touches the balcony on a summer morning. your sweater has a feel to it, it reminds me of mornings at the bread maker with my grandfather.
. 
this picture is of @ayush007

text:
though tanushree has decided to not label herself a christian she does professional to have had an encounter with jesus and is influenced by his teachings. but her recent trip to india (she's been living in the states for the past few years) where she inadvertently kick-started the metoo movement made me realize she is a lot like another biblical character - queen esther.
queen esther was a common jewish woman living in a foreign land with her uncle. the king of that land became unhappy with his wife, banished her and held a sort of contest to choose his new queen. and esther won the contest and became the queen. later, a few conspirators hatched a plan to kill all the jews. esther's uncle heard of the plan and planned with esther to approach the king and tell him if this plan and use her influence to change his mind. she does that and saves her people.
tanushree never imagined she would be used by god to kick start such a moment. and even though she might not have saved many people, she has through her bravery paved the way for other women to speak out and have a better chance to be heard than in previous years. and come on, both esther and tanushree were beauty queens!!

text:
(2/2) your voice seems so familiar. as if somewhere in the future we have already met. your elements have touched mine. your touch, my salvation. i move past this thought, and find the crumbled note in my hand a bit damp. i make promises with you i cannot keep. i wave, goodbye. goodbye, the voice in my head is louder. i walk away wondering if your eyes follow me.
did they ever?
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

if you know you know!

violence against women and girls is rooted in gender-based discrimination and social norms and gender stereotypes that perpetuate such violence. given the devastating effect violence has on women, efforts have mainly focused on responses and services for survivors. however, the best way to end violence against women and girls is to prevent it from happening in the first place by addressing its root and structural causes.

prevention should start early in life, by educating and working with young boys and girls promoting respectful relationships and gender equality. working with youth is a â€œbest betâ€ for faster, sustained progress on preventing and eradicating gender-based violence.Â while public policies and interventions often overlook this stage of life, it is a critical time when values and norms around gender equality are forged.

together we can achieve more........ oseni ibrahim

violence against women and girls is rooted in gender-based discrimination and social norms and gender stereotypes that perpetuate such violence. given the devastating effect violence has on women, efforts have mainly focused on responses and services for survivors. however, the best way to end violence against women and girls is to prevent it from happening in the first place by addressing its root and structural causes.

prevention should start early in life, by educating and working with young boys and girls promoting respectful relationships and gender equality. working with youth is a â€œbest betâ€ for faster, sustained progress on preventing and eradicating gender-based violence.Â while public policies and interventions often overlook this stage of life, it is a critical time when values and norms around gender equality are forged.

together we can achieve more........ oseni ibrahim

text:
churches, religion and god.
so cardinal george pell of the catholic church has been convicted for child sex abuse. the fuckery of this is exponential to the church and all it's high regard that they have of one another. 
when are we going to learn? 
there is no system that can keep us from god. 
from our truth. 
to have to get to god via a pastor or priest 
and have your sins absolved and the truth is 
that there is this happening inside it's doors,
is a mockery. 
but also it is time.
it is time for the truth to come out.
it is time to realise that the truth 
has always been held from you. 
as we rise as beings of a 5d reality 
we get to see the truth that we are. 
we never needed no church, 
no priest 
to tell us the sinners that we are. 
and that we were never good enough, 
holy enough or pure enough to be 
the god's we came to be.

we carry the divine within.
that makes us divine.
we never left creator. 
we are divine.

this place, this place called earth
is just a construct of our mind. 
and yes we get to play this sacred game called life.
but we also get to remember who the fuck we are!

we are divine.
we came from the divine.
and we never left.
we are all one.

these bodies make us feel seperate.
but we are one.
one with everything.
one with all.

these constructs are falling around us.
and this is what remains. 
you.
you and the divine.

fuck religion.
fuck the constructs.
fuck society that has kept us small.

step into the divine.
be that now!

it is done.
in one, in all, in love.
amen.
maria.

text:
in november 2017, at team of 30 advocates set out to touch lives of girls living on kalangala island. we went to different schools and communities plus landing sites to sensitise people about the benefits of educating girls and supporting them to realize their full potential. 
we also met girls at bery glaser 's place who we spent an evening with talking to them about their rights, the importance of keeping in school and the need to break the silence if they are sexually abused. 
none of the girls mentioned the torture they were going through and am sure it's because they were threatened and stopped from speaking out the truth.
we left with an impression that they were doing well, going to school,  having meals regularly and receiving medical care when they fell sick. 
all these were lies. 
they were all being sexually abused every night. those that refused were denied education sponsorship and meals sometimes while others were chased away.

i had the opportunity to speak one on one with some girls but non of them ever mentioned that they were being seriously harassed. some requested me to get them sponsors for their education ( now i understand that these could be the ones that had refused to give in the the demands of their master. 
these girls ran to this home to hide from the relatives that were sexually abusing them only to fall into a much bigger pit.
i feel so sad that they had to endure all this for years without help.
this home has been operating illegally and whereas some of the district officials in kalangala district were aware, they never closed up this home. the police in kalangala new about this but never helped the children.

in november 2017, at team of 30 advocates set out to touch lives of girls living on kalangala island. we went to different schools and communities plus landing sites to sensitise people about the benefits of educating girls and supporting them to realize their full potential. 
we also met girls at bery glaser 's place who we spent an evening with talking to them about their rights, the importance of keeping in school and the need to break the silence if they are sexually abused. 
none of the girls mentioned the torture they were going through and am sure it is because they were threatened and stopped from speaking out the truth.
we left with an impression that they were doing well, going to school,  having meals regularly and receiving medical care when they fell sick. 
all these were lies. 
they were all being sexually abused every night. those that refused were denied education sponsorship and meals sometimes while others were chased away.

i had the opportunity to speak one on one with some girls but non of them ever mentioned that they were being seriously harassed. some requested me to get them sponsors for their education ( now i understand that these could be the ones that had refused to give in the the demands of their master.

content note: pell, childhood sexual assault (no details). i haven't signed this yet but it feels right to share this painting i did today. this work is called "rise". it's a companion piece to the "climb" and "dive" paintings (which i need to individually photograph and put online) but is also separate. they're all about the continuous process of healing, of living with illness and trauma. 
they all have tension between the serene colours and the energetic brushmarks but "rise" is especially about childhood sexual assault. the person who assaulted me was a painter. for a long time after i kept making art, and then i mostly stopped. it hurt too much, triggered too much, and i was also punishing myself. last year i started painting again. this work is about the pain, yes, but also the reclamation. [image descriptions: photos of an abstract acrylic painting on a3 watercolour paper in perylene green, phthalo turquoise, raw sienna, and titanium white.]
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
a former senior trump campaign staffer monday filed a lawsuit in federal court against the president, accusing him of sexual assault during his 2016 campaign

alva johnson says trump grabbed her hand and kissed her without her consent ahead of a campaign rally in tampa. in an interview with the washington post, johnson said, â€œi immediately felt violated because i wasnâ€™t expecting it or wanting it. i can still see his lips coming straight for my face.â€ the lawsuit alleges that president trump forcibly kissed johnson in a campaign rv â€œin front of numerous other campaign officials.â€ johnson â€œfelt reduced to just another object of defendant trumpâ€™s unwanted sexual attention,â€ according to the lawsuit, filed in the u.s. district court for the middle district of florida in tampa.

white house press secretary sarah sanders denied the allegations in a statement to the washington post. â€œthis never happened and is directly contradicted by multiple highly credible eye witness accounts,â€ sanders wrote.

johnson also says she experienced racial discrimination while working for the president. â€œnot only did ms. johnson endure forcible kissing by her boss, she experienced race and gender discrimination as one of the few females and one of only a handful of african american people on the campaign payroll,â€ the lawsuit states.

johnson initially consulted an attorney in 2016 after the access hollywood tape release because she recognized a similarity with what happened to her, according to the lawsuit.

johnsonâ€™a attorney, hassan a. zavareei, in a news release, said she eventually decided to come forth. â€œwhen she saw what her work on the campaign had wroughtâ€”a president who mocks the #metoo movement and undermines the dignity of the office with his sexist and racist behaviorâ€”she decided to seek justice.â€ johnson is seeking unspecified damages for emotional pain and suffering, the post reported.

four people confirmed to the new yorker that johnson told them about the incident afterward, but two others johnson says were present at the time of the assault said they did not see it.

#usa

celebrating the silver jubilee, urvashi, the lead actor shared how magalir mattum was ahead of its time and spoke of workplace harassment and the male gaze. â€œto produce a project that tells the story from a womanâ€™s point of view was an audacious attempt. and, he (kamal haasan) selected actresses who are not known for their glamorous roles,â€ said urvashi crediting kamal hasan and  singeetham for the movie's success.

text:
what did you do last night? did you get stuck between sweaty bods on a grubby tram? did you shake your fist at traffic? maybe you raised a sweat over dirty laundry, un-chopped vegetables or unwashed dishes? maybe you just did it all silently...muttering to yourself.
.
did you bend your partners ear about another day objectified, victimised, ignored or overlooked for opportunities at work?
.
what if next monday night you could skip all that rubbish and just skip to your local pub instead?
.
monday 4th march @ 6:30-9:30pm
grace darling hotel - collingwood
.
a night of union choir, spoken word and power pantsuits. celebrating international womens day.
.
if you have a story, a burden, a confession...cut it loose at the open mic. there is nothing more liberating than liberating yourself in three minutes in front of a room full of strangers.
.
details and rsvp: facebook event via my profile: â€œi am woman, hear me (w)rawâ€
.
https://www.facebook.com/events/2256347871274683/?ti=
.
https://www.unionwomen.org.au/spoken_word_wrawfest
.
@amy_bodossian @zaynabf_____ @koraly_poet @melbspokenword .

.

text: i'd like to explain something to those who have not experienced the effects of childhood abuse. as we survivors grow older, all of the feelings and beliefs we had about ourselves during our abuse do not just go away when we become knowledgeable or gain awareness, or even when our life changes because of something new and exciting. they stay deep within our minds and in our hearts until we go in there and set them free. the effects that we suffered through during our teens and adulthood were felt and suffered through by all of those around us. some evil things too. but i'd like to say that the cause of those effects is by far much much more evil, yet it is the effects that are most talked about and vilified. i don't talk about it much but i suffer from ptsd and it's a daily struggle to live with it. it's far from over because there are still years of my childhood still hidden away in the darkest corners of my mind. i know that they must come to the light because just like with the other memories that came to light, it explained why i had been suffering certain effects throughout my life. my point is......the effects that we as victims of child abuse suffered were very bad yes.... and they need to be dealt with but...we as a society need to get to the root of the problem. stop the child abuse! victim to victor - #metoo #mentoo #solaceinchaos #childhoodsexualabusesurvivor #losangeles #atlanta #neworleans #philadelphia #chicago #book #film #writer #podcast @20thcenturyfox @nbc @hbo @showtime @lifetimemovies @ladygaga @terrycrews #london #australia

knowing i was a completely different person then as i am now. both physically and emotionally.

one had her whole life mapped out in front of her while the other barely makes it through the day ğŸ¦‹

a word of advice: 
these people have taken enough from you; your time, your body, your mind and most importantly your worth.

you are the same person. you are beautiful, strong and you are loved. 
you are the same person only stronger, smarter and more determined then every to conquer the world! whatever that may be to any individual. 
even if you feel alone, do not throw yourself away. 
fight for what you lost because unlike others, you will thrive. and conquer everything and anything that gets in the way of your goals and dreams. 
and because youâ€™ve seen the darkest parts of world world and survived.
anything is possible. 
if only you believe âœ¨

text:
it can be so easy for us to listen to the fear of our traumas. sometimes it even makes sense to listen to them because they are so good at convincing us something isn't right just because it creates a certain emotional reaction in us. 
more often than not though these fears keep us small, locked in our comfort zone and so the life that we dream can never be achieved because that life we dream of exists outside of the comfort zone.

text:
ğŸŒ»childhood sexual abuseğŸŒ»
.
i am a survivor of csa
.
i was sexually abused by a family friend when i was very young. around four or five, i donâ€™t remember the age. but i remember it all. it will never leave me
.
i was told to never tell my parents. and i didnâ€™t, for over ten years. i lived with a pervasive sense of â€œwrongnessâ€, boundarilessness and deep shame my whole childhood. i wanted to tell, but was terrified that i would be found out as a horrible girl, that i would be rejected and that this is what i deserved.

i revealed it to a boyfriend in my teens. we had a very deep unhealthy relationship and he was violent. as an abusive revenge tactic, after physically assaulting me, he told all my friends at school about it
.
they all said i was making it up for attention
.
i told my parents. it was reported to police. the police told my parents that there would not be enough evidence to prove him guilty in court because i was too young. the police also warned that i would be cross examined and have to tell my story in court in front of strangers; would i be comfortable with this? i opted out.
.
i have had layers of trauma in my life but this laid the foundation for the others to cut even deeper
.
this also laid the foundation for me to be abused and manipulated by more people in my life
.
i donâ€™t know where my abuser is, if he is alive, and i shudder to think that because i didnâ€™t have a voice to bring forth truth, that he has, and maybe even continues to hurt others
.
i share this off the back of some recent news in australia of cardinal george pell being convicted of childhood sexual abuse in the catholic church
.
for too long the voices of csa survivors have been locked up in the dark, and i want others to know that if you experienced this, you are not alone. you are not a shameful person. you are a beautiful innocent soul and what happened to you was wrong and horrible and there is hope for your restoration
.
iâ€™m proud to see people like my friend @metoowhatnow sharing his story and getting this incredibly common and devastating reality out into open public discussion
.
may the future be open to vulnerability. may we believe survivors 
#metoo

this is your life. you are the creator. the artist. you decide.

text:
day 56: 9 to 5...
mariah: for the 1980s, 9 to 5 was definitely revolutionary and the seeds of that frustration would spill over to where weâ€™re at now with #metoo and #timesup. the film is so resonant thereâ€™s talks of a sequel as sexual discrimination and harassment continue to plague our workplaces. a film that is humorous, biting, and demonstrates a future we hopefully are getting to in terms of equal pay, daycare, and overall better work conditions. jane fonda, lily tomlin, and dolly parton are a dream and their willingness to call out gender inequality is not to be forgotten â¤ï¸...
yasmin: what a time-warp treat. though produced in 1980, itâ€™s incredible how timely a film about inequality and sexism fits right into our modern day. we follow three women who fantasize about taking down their machismo boss, but a marijuana-induced fugue quickly becomes reality in this vintage satire. we still live in a world built for men by people of color and womxn, but it was incredible to see the dreams of flexible hours, in-house daycare, equal pay, and personalized work spaces. this is a film quite revolutionary for its time and we would gain so much by manifesting the world we deserve.

#chicagotheatretriathlon #9to5life #9to5 #9to5film #dollyparton #janefonda #lilytomlin #screentostage #9to5musical

text:
breakthrough. last week during my session, my therapist interrupted me and said, firmly, â€œstop thinking for other people.â€ itâ€™s easier said than done, of course. and i know that anxiety disorder is rooted in overthinking *everything* (and hashing out every possible scenario that hasnâ€™t even happened yet). but no one had ever explained it to me in these terms. if anxiety is a shroud that has been unceremoniously draped over my head, the cloth is a least clean now, and i can see some light shining through in places where there was only matted darkness before. â€¢
i know that this habit was borne of the abuse iâ€™ve been through. itâ€™s a coping mechanism iâ€™ve used to keep myself safe. â€œnever allow yourself to get into vulnerable situations -> never be vulnerable -> never get hurt again!â€ not so much. i have held myself back from so much potential joy through the years simply because iâ€™ve assumed the worst before itâ€™s even happened. iâ€™ve made decisions based solely on unfavorable  imaginary conversations that have only taken place within my mind. we all do this to an extent (judgement), but i was doing it to an unhealthy degree. vulnerability doesnâ€™t work that way. being an intelligent woman, iâ€™m sure iâ€™d claim to know that if someone spelled it out for me. and yetâ€¦ the subconscious is a motherf*Â¢&^r.  but now that iâ€™ve named- now that iâ€™ve called it on itâ€™s bullish!t- itâ€™s possible for me to catch and correct myself when i do it. 2019 is all about replacing old, unhealthy coping mechanisms with healthy new ones! âœ¨ğŸŒ±#anxiety #anxietydisorder #gad #therapy #mentalhealthawareness #mentalillness #mentalwellness #selflove #selfcare #survivor #survivoradvocate #believesurvivors #believewomen #believeblackwomen #rapesurvivor #sexualabuse #childhoodsexualabuse #csasurvivor#metoo #timesup #endrapeculture #metoomovement
